      <hedline>
        <hl1>Saving the Perishable</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Steve Giovinco letter agrees with Maxwell L Anderson's September 24 article on need to preserve perishable digital art (S)</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Maxwell L. Anderson's article ''Preserving the Perishable Art of the Digital Age'' [Sept. 24] was excellent not only because he surveyed the inherent problems for collectors of digital work and offered a passionate need to preserve it; more important, he actually raised the question of preservation when few curators or artists are discussing it.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Maxwell L. Anderson's article ''Preserving the Perishable Art of the Digital Age'' [Sept. 24] was excellent not only because he surveyed the inherent problems for collectors of digital work and offered a passionate need to preserve it; more important, he actually raised the question of preservation when few curators or artists are discussing it.</p>
        <p>Built-in obsolescence of new technology occurs exponentially: today's standard, the CD-ROM, is threatened by DVD, while computer power doubles every 18 months. It is this very technological consumption that makes digital work so emblematic of our time, yet so difficult to represent.</p>
        <p>STEVE GIOVINCO  Manhattan</p>
        <p>VIRTUAL MUSEUMS</p>
      </block>
    </body.content>
